The derivative of a polynomial is described by the [general Leibniz formula](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Leibniz_rule) which says that the nth derivative of a polynomial f(x) is f^{(n)}(x) = x^(n-1)*[n(n-1)!(f'(x) + f''(x) +... + f^(n-1)(x))]

This formula can be applied recursively and the code looks like this:
```python

def derivative(xs):
    def _derivative(n, xs):
        """ Calculate the (n)th derivative of polynomial. """
        if n == 1:
            return [1] * len(xs)
        elif n > 1:
            dx_i = xs
            for _ in range(n-2):
                dx_i = _derivative(n-1, xs)
            return xs * (n-1) * sum(dx_i)
    return [dx_i * len(xs) for dx_i in _derivative(len(xs)-1, xs)]
```

To get the derivative of a polynomial xs=[a0, a1,..., an] we apply this formula: dx_0 = an!*a_n dx_1 = (an-1)!(a_n a_n-1) dx_2 = (an-2)!(a_n a_n-1 a_n-2)... dx_n-2 = 1! a_0 and dx_n-1 = 0.

Thus, the code can be optimized to perform only the necessary computations by starting with the highest exponent of the polynomial and proceeding to lower exponents. 

The code looks like this:
```python
def derivative(xs):
    return [xs[i] * sum(range(n, -1, -1)) * fac(n) for i, n in enumerate(xs[1:])]

def fac(n):
    return 1 if n == 0 else n * fac(n-1)
```

