To compute the nth term of Collatz sequence, a certain number of iterations can be performed at most. To avoid exceeding the token limit, we can use the formula to determine the time complexity: time = n/2 + n/4 + n/8 +... + 1 = (n/2) \* (1 + 1/2 + 1/4 +... + 1/2^(log_2 n)) < n/2 \* (2 + 2/2 + 2/4 +... + 2/2^(log_2 n)) = O(log n).

We are dealing with an infinite loop. So, we cannot compute the total time complexity directly. However, we can still use the idea of the [harmonic series](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmonic_series_(mathematics)) to compute the time complexity. The sum of terms of the harmonic series is known to be O(log n). So we can upper bound the time complexity as follows: time <= n/2 \* (1/2 + 1/2 + 1/2 +... + 1/2) <= n/2 \* log 2, which is the upper bound of the time complexity.

